data.content:
Here's the complete migration:

## What breaks on .NET 8

| API | Problem |
|-----|---------|
| `Thread.Abort()` | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` (SYSLIB0006) |
| `Thread.Interrupt()` | Obsolete (SYSLIB0046 in .NET 9), unreliable even on Framework |

## Patterns found

1. **Cancellable work loop** — `while (true)` → check `CancellationToken`
2. **Blocking call interruption** — `ManualResetEvent.WaitOne()` → `WaitHandle.WaitAny` with token, or replace entirely with `Channel<T>`

## Pre-existing bug in original code

Multiple rapid `Enqueue()` calls race with the single `WaitOne`/`Reset` cycle — the `ManualResetEvent` can be `Set()` multiple times but only triggers one `Dequeue`, leaving items stranded.

---

## Migrated code (idiomatic .NET 8)

```csharp
using System.Threading.Channels;

public class EventProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private readonly Channel<string> _channel = Channel.CreateUnbounded<string>();
    private readonly CancellationTokenSource _cts = new();
    private Task? _runTask;

    public void Start()
    {
        _runTask = Task.Run(() => RunLoopAsync(_cts.Token));
    }

    private async Task RunLoopAsync(CancellationToken token)
    {
        try
        {
            await foreach (var item in _channel.Reader.ReadAllAsync(token))
            {
                Handle(item);
            }
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            // Clean shutdown — don't propagate
        }
    }

    public void Enqueue(string item)
    {
        if (!_channel.Writer.TryWrite(item))
            throw new InvalidOperationException("Channel is closed.");
    }

    public async Task StopAsync()
    {
        _channel.Writer.Complete();          // signal no more items
        _cts.CancelAfter(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5)); // timeout fallback
        if (_runTask is not null)
            await _runTask;
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        _cts.Dispose();
    }

    private void Handle(string item) { /* your logic */ }
}
```

## If you must keep synchronous threads

```csharp
public class EventProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private readonly ManualResetEvent _newEvent = new(false);
    private readonly CancellationTokenSource _cts = new();
    private readonly Queue<string> _queue = new();
    private readonly object _lock = new();
    private Thread? _thread;

    public void Start()
    {
        _thread = new Thread(RunLoop);
        _thread.Start();
    }

    private void RunLoop()
    {
        var handles = new WaitHandle[] { _newEvent, _cts.Token.WaitHandle };

        while (!_cts.Token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            // Wakes on either a new item OR cancellation
            int index = WaitHandle.WaitAny(handles);
            if (index == 1) break; // cancellation handle fired

            _newEvent.Reset();

            // Drain all queued items (fixes the original race bug)
            while (true)
            {
                string? item;
                lock (_lock)
                {
                    if (_queue.Count == 0) break;
                    item = _queue.Dequeue();
                }
                Handle(item);
            }
        }
    }

    public void Enqueue(string item)
    {
        lock (_lock) { _queue.Enqueue(item); }
        _newEvent.Set();
    }

    public void Stop()
    {
        _cts.Cancel();                // wakes WaitAny via token.WaitHandle
        _thread?.Join(5000);          // wait for clean exit
        // No Thread.Abort fallback — the loop cooperates
    }

    public void Dispose() => _cts.Dispose();

    private void Handle(string item) { /* your logic */ }
}
```

## Key pitfalls to watch

| Pitfall | Guidance |
|---------|----------|
| **`Thread.Abort` has no replacement** | There is no way to forcibly kill a thread in .NET 8. The loop *must* cooperate by checking the token. |
| **`WaitOne()` ignores cancellation** | Replace with `WaitHandle.WaitAny(new[] { event, token.WaitHandle })` so the thread wakes on cancel. |
| **Not draining the queue** | The original dequeued only one item per signal. Drain in a loop after waking to avoid lost items. |
| **Forgetting to dispose `CancellationTokenSource`** | It's `IDisposable` — leaking it causes timer/callback leaks. |
| **Catching `OperationCanceledException` and swallowing it** | Only catch at the top-level orchestration point. Let it propagate everywhere else. |

The `Channel<T>` version is strongly recommended — it eliminates the manual lock, the `ManualResetEvent`, and the drain-loop logic in one shot.
